<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Sets Stage for Bush's Speech  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The final image of the Republican National
Convention showed a podium laden with the sizable Bush clan and a
diverse display of the candidate's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   It was a picture-perfect end to George W. Bush's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And for Dan Rather, it brought to mind the founding fathers who
had gathered there in Philadelphia two centuries ago. Since that
time, said the CBS anchor, the political process ''has gone from
James Madison to Madison Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, in recent election years, the conventions
increasingly have seemed like infomercials meant to sell a
candidate to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   And to exasperate journalists. For TV correspondents, the
Republican gathering in its final day remained a toy they had
wearied of right out of the box, as they looked ahead to more of
the same at the Democratic Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But first, there was The Speech. Gov. Bush's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just hours away from the most important speech of his life,''
began Tom Brokaw at the top of ''NBC Nightly News.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the mantra of convention coverage Thursday, although soon
Bush introduced his own: his oft-repeated applause lines, ''They
have not led; we will'' and ''It won't be long now.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bush began speaking about 10 p.m. Eastern, all the
networks -- ABC, CBS, NBC and PBS plus cable networks CNN, Fox News
Channel, MSNBC and C-SPAN -- were on board.
</P>
<P>
   And by that time, everyone, it seemed, had already expressed
themselves on what Bush should or shouldn't say.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on NBC from the Minnesota governor's mansion, former
pro wrestler Jesse Ventura, a political independent, body-slammed
both parties for their rhetoric: ''They cite a problem. They blame
the other side for it. Then they tell you they're going to fix it.
But they never tell you how.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Bush had begun, even the staging of his speech was
deconstructed.
</P>
<P>
   NBC News analyst Howard Fineman pointed out how decorative ferns
had been repositioned on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Former Republican speech writer Peggy Noonan marveled at the
downsized, college-classroom sort of lectern the nominee would use.
''It's utterly exposed, it's utterly undefended, it's utterly
observed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, a few minutes later, Noonan was on Fox News Channel, where
she blamed the media for the convention's mild-mannered tone.
Republicans, she said, ''don't want to give any excuse for the ...
electronic media to come at them saying, 'You're mean! You're
harsh!'''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's unexpected hospitalization of former President Ford
from a stroke had given the media a few hours' break from the
boilerplate convention. Through an accident of time and place, the
illness of a man who left the White House a quarter-century ago was
upstaging the man who wants to be its next resident.
</P>
<P>
   But as the networks supplied updates Thursday on Ford's
improving condition, viewers might have wondered if they were
learning more about the medical cause of strokes than how the
candidate aimed to improve education.
</P>
<P>
   Political humorists were happy to fill the gap. On CNN, Al
Franken cracked that, ''Thanks to George W., 60 percent of high
school seniors in Texas now read at a higher level than the
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the Internet, the Modern Humorist's Web site
posted an ''advance'' copy of Bush's speech, titled ''United I
Stand'':
</P>
<P>
   ''To my parents, Dad and Bar, great parents, only a so-so
president. Just kidding, Dad, but you still don't get to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   And interviewed on CNN, E! fashion commentator Joan Rivers
declared that politicians' couture is fun to lampoon. ''You know
these women had to think: 'What can I wear to look good, and yet
not offend anybody?'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rivers had just explained politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
