<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, Aug. 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Reaches Out to America
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- George W. Bush appealed to the nation Thursday night to
''grant me a mandate'' to lead and break the cycle of partisan Washington
feuding. Bush told cheering delegates he would help ''end the politics of fear''
and promised to work together with Democrats on pressing problems, including
shoring up the Social Security system and more accountability in education
policy. The cheers grew loudest when he vowed to pursue tax fairness and
anti-abortion laws. The Texas governor began his acceptance speech with a small
salute to the audience.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Accepts Republican Presidential Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- George W. Bush accepted the Republican presidential
nomination Thursday night, presenting himself as an outsider who will return
''civility and respect'' to Washington politics. ''They have not led,'' he said
of the incumbent Democrats. ''We will.'' Republicans ended their 37th National
Convention in a mood of exuberant optimism, but Bush warned of a hard fight
ahead. ''I believe this will be a tough race, down to the wire,'' he said. Four
times, the two-term Texas governor said the Democrats had failed leadership
tests -- on tending to the military, on education, on Social Security and
Medicare and moral leadership.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Airlines Grounds 18 Jets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alaska Airlines is grounding up to 18 Boeing MD-80
airliners for inspections of a part implicated in last January's crash that
killed 88 people, federal regulators said Thursday. The airline reported to the
Federal Aviation Administration that tools used to check jackscrews may have
produced incorrect readings. The jackscrew assembly consists of a nut that rides
up and down a screw as it turns to lift and lower the stabilizer. There are no
indications of problems, the FAA said, but the agency is alerting other airlines
using MD-80 planes -- as well as DC-9 jets, which are also affected -- to check
their planes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore VP List Has Six Names
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore's list of vice presidential choices for
Campaign 2000 is down to six people. The four leading prospects are from the
Senate: Evan Bayh of Indiana, John Edwards of North Carolina, John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut. House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt and New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen round out the short list, a
Democratic source familiar with the vice president's thinking said. Both have
said they don't want the job.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Canada Navy Boards U.S.-Owned Ship
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Backed by war ships, Canadian troops dropped
from a helicopter and seized control of a U.S.-owned vessel off its Atlantic
coast Thursday, after the ship refused to deliver its cargo of Canadian military
supplies because of a monthlong contract dispute. The navy boarded the 750-foot
freighter, the GTS Katie, about 140 miles off Newfoundland. The Katie was being
escorted to Montreal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
60 Wildfires Burn in U.S. West
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- About 60 large wildfires covering more than 637,500
acres were burning Thursday in Western states. ''Things are not improving, I
have to be honest and say that,'' said Ed Waldapfel, a spokesman for the
National Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho. ''Even though we are having
some successes, we're having more fires start each day than we are getting fires
put out.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reno Will Speed E-Mail Review
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno said Thursday she will
accelerate a promised review of the FBI's anti-crime e-mail surveillance system
and do everything she can to calm privacy advocates' worries about it. Reno
reiterated that she will have an independent panel of experts critique the inner
workings of ''Carnivore,'' the FBI's system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NASA Mission Costs Soar
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Proposed budgets for new NASA space exploration missions
are rising as much as 40 percent in the aftermath of back-to-back Mars failures
and the agency is considering canceling some projects, a key administrator said
Thursday. Nothing has been canceled yet, said Ed Weiler, NASA's associate
administrator for space science. He flatly denied rumors that he had already cut
a mission to Pluto.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Lower at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks declined Friday morning. The Nikkei shed 39.59
points to 15,774.85 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indians 5, Devil Rays 1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Jason Bere pitched another strong game for
Cleveland, giving up four hits in eight innings as the Indians beat the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays 5-1 Wednesday night. Bere has won both his starts since being
acquired in a seven-player deal with the Milwaukee Brewers last Friday. Bere
struck out eight and walked two.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
