<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Parcells among friends posting bail for disgraced financier  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Former penny-stock tycoon Robert E. Brennan,
scrambling to make $500,000 bail on bankruptcy fraud charges, got
some help from former NFL coach Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, now director of football operations for the New York
Jets, was among those who gathered Thursday at the federal
courthouse here to post cash or securities for the disgraced
financier.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells chatted about deep-sea fishing with three other
associates of Brennan while waiting for a receipt at the court
clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speak to a reporter about Brennan, who had just
pleaded innocent to the charges at his arraignment at federal court
in Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells posted $150,000 of the $500,000 federal bail set
Tuesday after Brennan's arrest, according to a legal source who
requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   About $236,000 will be posted in the form of mutual funds, said
defense lawyer Michael Critchley. He declined to say who owns those
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, of Sea Girt, coached the New York Giants to two Super
Bowl victories, and also coached the New England Patriots and the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   He is among the members of a private golf course developed at
Brennan's former horse farm in Colts Neck, Due Process Stables,
according to people familiar with the bankruptcy case.
</P>
<P>
   The property is among the assets seized to satisfy Brennan's
creditors, although Brennan still has an apartment in a gated
community there.
</P>
<P>
   He has been under house arrest at the property since Tuesday,
aside from court appearances, while awaiting the posting of the
$500,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan arrived at the Newark courthouse to finalize his bail
shortly after Parcells left.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a lot of nice friends,'' said Brennan, a New Jersey
native whose official residence is in Juno Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed optimism about his case: ''I'm just going to deal
with it responsibly and bring it to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he drove away in a green Audi convertible with Florida
plates.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 56, was also charged Tuesday by state authorities in
connection with his bankruptcy, and was released on $250,000 bail
soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Critchley declined to say who posted that money.
</P>
<P>
   Once the federal bail is complete, Brennan is allowed to stay in
New Jersey, New York or Florida, but must use a commercial carrier,
not a private aircraft, for travel.
</P>
<P>
   The two indictments unsealed with his arrest charge that Brennan
attempted to hide from creditors over $500,000 he got from cashing
casino chips less than a month after he filed for bankruptcy in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   They are the first criminal charges ever faced by Brennan after
two decades of clashes with stock regulators.
</P>
<P>
   He became publicly known in the 1980s through his television
commercials for his former flagship brokerage, First Jersey
Securities Inc., stepping off a helicopter and urging viewers to
''come grow with us.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of his bankruptcy proceeding, he had to sell his
interest in and resign as chairman of International Thoroughbred
Breeders Inc., which operated two New Jersey horse tracks, Garden
State Park and Freehold Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   During his arraignment in Trenton, U.S. District Court Judge
Garrett E. Brown Jr. allowed Brennan to waive his right to change
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose after prosecutors asserted that Critchley has a
conflict of interest because he is one of Brennan's creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan quietly answered the judge's questions, saying he
understood that Critchley's interests could run counter to his own
and he that he knowingly waived his right to change counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Critchley said Brennan owes him about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Critchley said the government's case is based solely on
documents from a Las Vegas casino, The Mirage. Those documents, he
contends, are wrong and ''fundamentally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Trial dates have not been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
