<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jays 3, Rangers 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Frank Castillo won his seventh straight decision
as the Toronto Blue Jays ended their six-game losing streak, 3-1
over the Texas Rangers on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo (8-5) hasn't lost since June 1. The right-hander
allowed just one run on four hits in seven innings. He struck out
four and didn't walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing consecutive singles to lead off the sixth,
Castillo turned a double play by making a sprawling catch in front
of the mound on a ball hit by Dave Martinez. He then threw to
second to double up Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo, who barely made the club out of spring training, has
been Toronto's second best starter this season. He's won seven of
his last nine starts, and has gone at least seven innings in six of
those starts.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Woodward, who entered the game hitting .188, hit a
tiebreaking two-out single off Kenny Rogers in the sixth to give
Toronto a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers (10-9) allowed two runs on seven hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Jays went ahead 3-1 on Shannon Stewart's RBI infield single
in the eighth off Jeff Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Guthrie, acquired by Toronto on Monday from Tampa Bay,
struck out Chad Curtis -- the only batter he faced -- to end the
eighth inning. Billy Koch pitched the ninth for his 25th save in 29
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler's 10th homer, a solo shot in the second gave Texas a
1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Rogers allowed a double to Jose Cruz, and a walk to Darrin
Fletcher in the bottom half, Marty Cordova tied it with a single.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Castillo was 1-5 after 11 starts. ... Toronto DH Brad
Fullmer broke two bats on consecutive swings in the fifth inning.
... Toronto's Raul Mondesi, on the 15-day disabled list with
ligament damage in his right elbow, played catch before the game.
... Kapler has six home runs in his last 15 games. He extended his
hitting streak to 17 games. ... Guthrie took the loss in his Blue
Jays debut Wednesday at Oakland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
