<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museums Seek Convention Collectables  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE FEINSILBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- To the Republican convention of political
junkies, the Smithsonian Institution dispatched two political junk
collectors.
</P>
<P>
   The mission of Harry Rubenstein and Larry Bird, curators at the
Smithsonian's National Museum of American History in Washington,
was to procure memorabilia to add to the 90,000 objects already in
the museum's political history collection.
</P>
<P>
   Funny hat? Larry and Harry wanted it. Screaming poster? They
snagged it. Catchy button? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   They left for home loaded with stuff. They snagged one of the
green signs carried by farm state delegates that showed a tractor
and played on the George Bush's baseball background. ''Bush Farm
Team,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   They got a rattle noisemaker with a pompom on it, a promise from
a Delaware delegate that he'd mail them a tri-corner hat worn on
the convention floor, a red ''sponge noodle'' -- a long piece of
foam rubber that is shaken in the air. And a poster saluting Bush's
wife (''Laura 4 First Lady'').
</P>
<P>
   They were impressed that delegates brought plank cardboard onto
the floor and made signs to suit the moment. Massachusetts
delegates who had been pledged to John McCain before he released
them made signs reading, ''Massachusetts McCainiacs for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   They failed, though, to snag a Bush-Cheney banner that was
rolled up but unfurled from a huge balloon upon Dick Cheney's
nomination. The balloonmeister was afraid if he let them cut free
one of the banners others would get the same idea.
</P>
<P>
   Their prize catch, the one item that, in a hundred years, will
say to museum visitors, ''Republicans in the year 2000,'' was one
of the 360-degree interactive cameras that provided convention
coverage for the Pseudo.com web site.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the first Internet convention,'' said Bird.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, at the GOP conclave in San Diego, Calif., the prize was
simpler: a handmade Dole hat. Everyone in the Ohio delegation wore
one.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had gone to the trouble of covering a balloon with
papier mache, spray painting it yellow, then pasting on green
cardboard fronds. The result was a hat that looked like a
pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple. ... Dole pineapple. ... Dole. ... Bob Dole. Get it?
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the pineapple hat is now a Smithsonian artifact.
Before showing it off to a visitor, Bird carefully pulled on white
gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading a delegate to give up a piece of political
memorabilia isn't always easy. If they can't snag it on the spot,
the curators hand a business card to the possessor and hope he'll
mail it to them after the convention. Sometimes it works.
</P>
<P>
   ''So much of this stuff is ephemeral, designed for the moment,''
said Rubenstein. ''We're there for the moment between the
convention and the trash can.''
</P>
<P>
   Too late they learned about a protest sign that Texas delegates
painted and waved while Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., an announced
homosexual, addressed the convention. ''There Is A Way Out,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sighed Bird: ''That sign is now in a landfill somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The curators aren't interested only in homemade stuff. They
haunted vendors' tables, bagging elephants in every manifestation.
Later this month they'll go to Los Angeles, when the Democrats
meet, to harvest donkey stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Bird says political paraphernalia plays a role in conventions
beyond levity. The delegates have no direct way to communicate with
the party leaders, he said. So what they wear speaks for them.
</P>
<P>
   He illustrates with a yellow scarf what abortion-rights
delegates wore in 1996 in opposition to the GOP plank that called
for a constitutional amendment outlawing abortion. ''Yank the
Plank,'' said the scarves.
</P>
<P>
   Splotches of waving yellow made the point that year that not
everyone liked the platform's anti-choice plank. ''A kind of subtle
debate,'' said Bird.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian holds far more in its collection than it could
possibly put on display, but the best of what the curators captured
here will go into an exhibition, ''The American Presidency,''
opening in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-04-00 0101 </TRAILER>
