<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis Moving To West Bank  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALMON, West Bank (AP) -- Last week, just days after Israeli
negotiators discussed handing this part of the West Bank over to
the Palestinians, Orly Tel-Kar and her husband moved to a tiny
Jewish settlement near the Palestinian city of Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the intensifying peace talks, they are among about 560
families that have settled in the West Bank this summer, according
to the head of a regional council.
</P>
<P>
   Some are there as a political statement, demonstrating their
belief that the West Bank belongs to the Jews, not the
Palestinians. Others are lured by subsidized housing prices and
open spaces away from crowded cities.
</P>
<P>
   All could lose their new homes if the Israelis and Palestinians
reach a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But many settlers, including Tel-Kar, are betting that will not
happen. They took heart from the failure of the Israeli-Palestinian
summit at Camp David outside Washington last month, when Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat were
unable to agree on a peace framework.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we moved in the Camp David talks had already collapsed,''
Tel-Kar said. ''Who knows, maybe Barak's next attempt will fail,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 Israelis live in 144 settlements in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip. Barak favors keeping blocs of settlements under
Israeli control, while carving up the West Bank so the Palestinians
would get more than 90 percent of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The future of settlements like Talmon, near Palestinian cities,
would be cloudy under Barak's plan. Either they would be dismantled
or the settlers would have to live under Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians demand that all the settlements be removed.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,300 housing units are under construction in the West
Bank, according to Peace Now, a dovish watchdog group. About 4,200
others are completed but empty.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Cohen, a landscape architect living in this hilltop
settlement, said people here are aware of the plan to evacuate
isolated settlements.
</P>
<P>
   But they have an ideological commitment to settling in the West
Bank coupled with a desire for quality of life, said Cohen, 31,
wearing the crocheted skullcap characteristic of the Orthodox
Jewish settlers who lead the drive to retain the territory for
religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of settlers come to the West Bank for earthly
reasons. ''They don't want to live in the urban sprawl of greater
Tel Aviv,'' Cohen said. ''They are looking for clear mountain air,
a fine view, a crime-free community and good schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly because of government subsidies, settlement housing is a
fraction of the cost of city apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Pinhas Wallerstein, the head of Binyamin Regional Council, said
that in his region -- which includes Talmon -- 3,000 housing units
have been started this year and 1,400 have been completed. The
Housing Ministry confirmed the figures.
</P>
<P>
   Six families have settled in Talmon in the past two months and
nine more are due to move in by September, said Meira Dolev, a
member of the absorption committee at Talmon. That is a 15 percent
increase in single summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people expected a drop in the numbers due to the Camp
David negotiations,'' Dolev said, ''but it just didn't happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-04-00 0104 </TRAILER>
