<HEADLINE> GOPs Look Towards Local Races  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Maybe it's just the flush that comes from a
smooth convention, a healthy bounce in the polls and days of
partying.
</P>
<P>
   But state Republican leaders leave their national convention
Friday with hopes, even expectations, that the Bush-Cheney ticket
will push them to victory in uphill and tight local races.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to happen,'' said Morton Blackwell, a national
committeeman from Virginia, likening George W. Bush to Ronald
Reagan for his personality and ability to bring together opposing
wings of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Take Indiana, where GOP Rep. David McIntosh hopes to topple a
sitting governor, Democrat Frank O'Bannon. The challenger is
getting help on the campaign trail from Bush, Blackwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana race is just one of scores of competitive battles
across the nation -- for Congress, control of legislatures, even
referendums.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the top of the ticket is someone you really believe in and
you have faith that they are doing the right thing, that buoys
everyone in the campaigns,'' said Matt Denny, Montana's state
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the latest results: polls that show Bush went from a
dead heat with Al Gore to a double-digit lead; and a remarkably
unified Republican Party, in sharp contrast to divisions in 1992
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some went so far to hope for the nationwide coattails that
Ronald Reagan brought in 1980; others were more cautious, saying
it's far too early for such expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, many conservatives and moderates say, their
differences seem less important than the goal of taking back the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   If the unity and energy here can translate into enthusiasm among
GOP voters at home, that will benefit tight state races, said Paul
Helmke, the former GOP mayor of Fort Wayne, Ind. He blamed his
unsuccessful Senate bid in 1998, in part, on a lack of energy among
Republican voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't have to change anybody's mind from 'D' to 'R,'''
Helmke said. Just get your supporters to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Republicans are really energized, as they say they are,
they might turn out and vote, and vote for the lower races as
well,'' said Roger Hartley, who teaches American politics at
Roanoke College in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Republican hope in the race for governor in Indiana,
in Sen. Rod Grams' re-election effort in Minnesota, in a South
Carolina fight against a lottery pushed by a Democratic governor.
And in Washington state, where the fight is on for control of the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a numbers man,'' said Mike Gaston, a chemical engineer and
Washington state committeeman. ''A 2 or 3 percent Bush bump, which
we fully expect, will turn the House to a Republican majority and,
more importantly, take back the state Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this affair in Philadelphia is just one side of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than a week, Democrats convene in Los Angeles,
hoping to counter the GOP bounce and energize their voter base.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm guessing that the Democratic delegates will be saying the
same thing,'' said Professor June Speakman, who teaches politics at
Roger Williams University in Bristol, R.I. She's also active in
local Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans here remained cautious. ''It could change
yet,'' Helmke said. ''Elections aren't won in August.''
</P>
<P>
   But as leaders and candidates return home, the message came
clear.
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh tried it out with his supporters at a reception speech:
''We can say to the people of Indiana, you can have the same great
leadership you have with George W. Bush in the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-04-00 0111 </TRAILER>
