<HEADLINE> Milosevic Said Scared of Elections  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright says the
opposition to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic must present a
united front for next month's national elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The important thing is for the opposition to solidify, present
a single candidate and get on with the elections,'' Albright said
Thursday at a joint press briefing with Spanish Foreign Minister
Josep Pique.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is acting illegally and provocatively because the
elections have him ''running scared,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Milosevic changed the constitution of the Yugoslav
federation to allow himself to run for two more four-year terms. He
called the upcoming elections under conditions that favor him and
his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome earlier this week, Albright sought unsuccessfully to
persuade opposition groups from Serbia and Montenegro to compete in
the elections. They are boycotting, partly because they consider
the process unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no doubt in anybody's mind that this election is
going to take place ... and that it will take place in unfair
circumstances where the media is under control and the opposition
is being intimidated,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And yet it is very evident that the bulk of the opposition,
even with this threat, is going to participate in the elections,
and we support them in this effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Among others, Albright has discussed the issue with Milo
Djukanovic, the president of Montenegro, Serbia's junior partner in
the Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   She said they discussed how Djukanovic's party could be helpful
to the opposition without participating in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/yutoc.html
</P>
