<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Congo Violating Peace Accord  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Congo is failing to live up to its
commitments under a year-old peace agreement and thereby preventing
deployment of thousands of U.N. observers, the United States told a
special envoy of Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Congo's Human Rights Minister Leonard She Okitundu said the
government wants the U.N. force deployed -- but only in conflict
areas where it can monitor the cease-fire and withdrawal of Rwandan
and Ugandan troops.
</P>
<P>
   With last year's cease-fire shattered by heavy fighting, and the
Congolese government accused of stonewalling on implementing the
peace accord, Okitundu flew to New York to address a closed-door
Security Council meeting Thursday on behalf of Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   The council has authorized a U.N. force of 5,537 troops and
observers with a mandate to oversee the cease-fire, the withdrawal
of foreign troops and the disarming of Rwandan Hutu militiamen. The
Hutu militiamen are responsible for the 1994 Rwanda genocide and
have been fighting alongside Congolese government troops.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, only about 200 U.N. military observers have
been deployed, mainly because of security problems. Last week,
Kabila refused to allow the first armed U.N. peacekeepers in the
capital, Kinshasa, and Mbandaka, a key river port.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.N. force's mandate due to expire Aug. 31, and the
United Nations reviewing its role in the country, Okitundu's visit
gave Security Council members a chance to express their frustration
at what U.S. deputy ambassador Nancy Soderberg called the greatest
crisis in Africa today.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and his allies, Namibia, Angola and Zimbabwe, signed the
cease-fire agreement last year in Lusaka, Zambia. So did Rwanda and
Uganda, which back rebels who took up arms in August 1998 to oust
Kabila from power.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese government troops recently launched a major offensive,
Soderberg noted, and rebels have also advanced beyond the
cease-fire line. The government has also failed to make any
progress on initiating an inter-Congolese dialogue, as called for
in the accord, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Until the signatories recognize that the peace accord isn't
working, Soderberg warned, the United Nations can do little to move
forward with the deployment of U.N. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Okitundu said in an interview that he told the council it should
separate the issue of external aggression against Congo from the
country's internal problems -- and not make democratization a
prerequisite for the withdrawal of foreign forces.
</P>
<P>
   He also called the allegations of cease-fire violations
''unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Okitundu said Congo asked for the U.N. mission to come to the
country to help recover its sovereignty and territorial integrity,
and to accompany Rwandan and Ugandan troops to the border to ensure
that they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila is expected to meet Annan's special representative Kamel
Morjane in the next few days to decide whether armed U.N.
peacekeepers can deploy, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-04-00 0126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000804.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activists Support Malaysia's Anwar  </HEADLINE>
By ALVIN UNG
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- About 500 supporters of jailed
politician Anwar Ibrahim gathered Friday outside the Kuala Lumpur
High Court to protest the postponement of the verdict in the sodomy
case against the former deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Holding portraits of Anwar and shouting ''Reformasi,'' the Malay
word for political reform, the protesters scuffled with police who
tried to push them away from the main street in front of the
courthouse. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders said at least three protesters were arrested.
Police declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''The postponement of Anwar's verdict has been influenced by the
cowardly political masters,'' said Mohamed Ezam Mohamed Nor, a
leader of the opposition National Justice Party.
</P>
<P>
   He and other protesters demanded that Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad heed growing dissatisfaction with his 19-year rule and
resign.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move Thursday, the High Court announced that Judge
Ariffin Jaka's verdict was not ready.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition activists say the decision not to announce the
verdict in the yearlong trial Friday was driven by fear of a
massive anti-government rally near the courthouse. The government
denied that had anything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Local rights activists, opposition leaders and supporters of
Anwar had announced plans to assemble outside the court during the
verdict, which would have capped a trial that has raised concerns
about the Malaysian judiciary and the country's politics.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old politician was fired by Mahathir in September
1998. He was soon arrested and put on trial on charges of
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar has denied all the accusations against him during his two
trials since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His imprisonment -- including a beating in custody by the
then-police chief -- has catalyzed calls for reform, opened a window
on human rights abuses and brought the opposition to band together
in elections last year.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations have rocked Kuala Lumpur sporadically since
Anwar's sacking and arrest as his supporters have tried to keep
alive his campaign for more liberal politics in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   A guilty verdict could add several years to the six-year jail
sentence that Anwar was given for corruption last year. Under
Malaysian law, sodomy is punishable by maximum imprisonment of 20
years and whipping by a rattan cane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
