<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greystone counselor accused of sexually assaulting patient  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) - A counselor at Greystone Park
Psychiatric Hospital charged with sexually assaulting a female
patient claims he and the woman had a consensual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Jared Alford, 43, of Newark, was arrested Wednesday and charged
with sexual assault and officials misconduct. Police said the
nine-year veteran employee had sex with a 50-year-old patient from
Bergen County just over a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual relationships are forbidden between patients and
employees at state mental institutions and are considered sexual
assault under state law.
</P>
<P>
   Another patient told police about the situation, and authorities
said Alford admitted to the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''Alford claims he had a real relationship with this woman, that
he had strong feelings for her,'' Pam Ronan, a spokeswoman for the
state Department of Human Services, told The Star-Ledger of Newark
for Friday's editions. ''But that is improper conduct; an employee
cannot have sexual relations with a patient under any
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Alford, a residential living specialist at the institution,
helped patients nearing discharge to relearn living skills before
returning home, Ronan said. The woman, who was civilly committed to
Greystone in March, lived in the hospital's cottage for recovering
patients, where Alford worked.
</P>
<P>
   Greystone, scheduled to be closed in three years, has faced
harsh criticism for a series of sex-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a policy prohibiting patients at Greystone Park
Psychiatric Hospital from having sex, at least 12 mentally impaired
patients have become pregnant while being treated at the Parsippany
facility since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And in the early 1990s, a series of sexual attacks on patients
by employees led to a state Senate hearing about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman in April ordered that the hospital be
closed in three years, after decades of problems that included
attacks on patients, patient suicides and overcrowding.
</P>
</TEXT>
