<HEADLINE> Couric Picks Up Southern Accent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Katie Couric has begun picking up
different speech patterns since she hired two Birmingham natives as
personal assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been saying 'y'all' and 'hey' a lot lately,'' said
Couric, host of NBC's ''Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Allsbrook, 25, handles Couric's scheduling and other
professional chores. Marlowe Mitchell, 24, handles Couric's
correspondence. Both are from the Birmingham suburb of Mountain
Brook.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as Katie met Marlowe, she was like, 'Oh my gosh,
here's my Southern team,''' Allsbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   Couric's great-grandfather was from Eufaula, Ala. An 1850 Greek
Revival house in Eufaula -- the Couric-Smith House -- recently was
featured on a ''Today'' segment in which Couric went searching for
her roots.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are smart, hardworking and fun to be around,'' Couric
said of her assistants. ''And, obviously, the Alabama connection is
a plus. I think everybody in New York who calls my office enjoys
their Southern accents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
