<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, Aug. 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
George W. Bush Accepts GOP Presidential Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Opening a 95-day countdown to the election, Republicans
George W. Bush and Dick Cheney charge side-by-side into Midwest battleground
states Friday pledging to ''use these good times for great goals'' if they
succeed in winning the White House. The Texas governor claimed the GOP
nomination Thursday night in a deafening convention celebration and deluge of
balloons and confetti. There was a mood of exuberant optimism about Bush's
chances -- he is ahead in the polls -- but he cautioned that ''this will be a
tough race, down to the wire'' with Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Justice Dept. To Indict GOP Donor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Federal prosecutors have informed a major Republican
donor they will seek an indictment this month alleging environmental crimes in
Texas that date back five years, officials familiar with the investigation said.
The case against Koch Petroleum promises to open a window on the relationship
between oil companies and Texas regulators amid an election in which Democrats
are suggesting Gov. George W. Bush's administration has gone easy on polluters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S.: Congo Violating Peace Accord
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Congo is failing to live up to its commitments under a
year-old peace agreement and thereby preventing deployment of thousands of U.N.
observers, the United States told a special envoy of Congolese President Laurent
Kabila. Congo's Human Rights Minister Leonard She Okitundu said the government
wants the U.N. force deployed -- but only in conflict areas where it can monitor
the cease-fire and withdrawal of Rwandan and Ugandan troops. With last year's
cease-fire shattered by heavy fighting, and the Congolese government accused of
stonewalling on implementing the peace accord, Okitundu flew to New York to
address a closed-door Security Council meeting Thursday on behalf of Kabila.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Education Remains Top Priority
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elementary and secondary school workers accounted for
almost 40 percent of the country's 14.7 million state and local government
employees in 1999, Census Bureau figures show. An agency report being released
Friday said there were 5.76 million full-time school workers, or 39.2 percent of
the state and local government total. In 1998, they accounted for 39.7 percent,
or 5.72 million of the 14.4 million total. Higher education employees were next,
at 1.7 million in 1999, followed by hospital employees at 952,301.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ford Plays It Safe With Larger SUVs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. might have promised to increase the
fuel economy of its sport utility vehicles, but a new version of the Ford
Explorer was built using the formula the world's No. 2 maker of cars and trucks
has found lucrative so far -- bigger and stronger. The 2002 version of the
Explorer, the industry's top-selling SUV, offers a more powerful engine and more
interior space over the current model. Ford made few stylistic changes to the
popular SUV, though, having learned a costly lesson a few years ago, when a
jarring redesign of the Taurus sedan drove many customers away.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Airlines Grounds 18 Jets
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alaska Airlines is grounding up to 18 Boeing MD-80
airliners for inspections of a part implicated in last January's crash that
killed 88 people, federal regulators said Thursday. The airline reported to the
Federal Aviation Administration that tools used to check jackscrews may have
produced incorrect readings. The jackscrew assembly consists of a nut that rides
up and down a screw as it turns to lift and lower the stabilizer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore VP List Has Six Names
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore's list of vice presidential choices for
Campaign 2000 is down to six people. The four leading prospects are from the
Senate: Evan Bayh of Indiana, John Edwards of North Carolina, John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut. House Democratic leader Dick
Gephardt and New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen round out the short list, a
Democratic source familiar with the vice president's thinking said. Both have
said they don't want the job.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Lower at Midday
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks declined Friday morning. The Nikkei shed 39.59
points to 15,774.85 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Diamondbacks 8, Braves 4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Luis Gonzalez drove in five runs in his second two-homer game
in four days and the Arizona Diamondbacks ended Andy Ashby's five-game winning
streak with an 8-4 victory Thursday night over the Atlanta Braves. Gonzalez had
a three-run home run in the first, an RBI double in the third and a solo homer
in the fifth, all off Ashby, as the Diamondbacks took two of three from Atlanta.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
