<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suharto Paperwork To Be Filed Monday  </HEADLINE>
By IRWAN FIRDAUS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- An indictment alleging massive
corruption by former dictator Suharto will be filed in a Jakarta
court on Monday, prosecutors said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, prosecutors formally charged Suharto, 79, with
skimming off $570 million in state funds through a complex network
of charities that he controlled during his 32-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   They allege the money bankrolled huge business empires for his
family and cronies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The indictment and a dossier detailing the case will be
submitted to a judge in the South Jakarta District Court on
Monday,'' said Yushar Yahya, a spokesman at the attorney general's
office.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was not certain whether Suharto, who is under house
arrest, would attend Monday's hearing, which will be largely
procedural.
</P>
<P>
   Yahya said prosecutors hope a trial can start within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's defense attorneys maintain he is too ill to go before
a judge and raised doubts that a trial would start soon.
</P>
<P>
   They claim a series of strokes have damaged Suharto's brain and
impaired his memory and ability to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, who was forced to quit office in May 1998 amid bloody
student protests and riots, has denied any wrongdoing. If
convicted, he could be sentenced to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Current President Abdurrahman Wahid has offered to pardon
Suharto if the stolen money is surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the case holds immense symbolic importance as a test of
Indonesia's resolve to fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Some estimates put the wealth of Suharto's relatives at $40
billion -- a figure his family denies. They also say there is no
Suharto family fortune stashed abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Marzuki Darusman, a human rights activist
during Suharto's reign, has said the former autocrat must face
trial, and cited recent independent medical tests that declared
Suharto fit enough to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's court hearing will coincide with the start of a
potentially stormy session of the People's Consultative Assembly,
Indonesia's supreme legislative body.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid is expected to face a hostile reception from lawmakers who
accuse him of failing to fix Indonesia's massive economic and
social problems.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Suharto's legal team, Juan Felix Tampubolon, has
said court proceedings against his client have been timed to
bolster Wahid's flagging popularity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
