<HEADLINE> Dow Up 8; Nasdaq Ahead 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose modestly Friday on employment data
that offered cautious optimism that an extremely tight job market
was easing slightly.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 7.69 at 10,714.27, having fallen back from a quick
upward move after the release of U.S. employment figures for July.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 5.76 at 1,458.32, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 15.08 at 3,774.96, slipping from a gain of more than 70
points earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate was unchanged at 4 percent in
July, close to a three-decade low, despite the loss of 108,000
payroll jobs during the month, the biggest setback in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the losses resulted from 290,000 temporary government
workers laid off in July because their work on the census was
finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department report showed private payrolls actually
rose by 138,000 during the month. However, analysts noted that last
month's gain in private sector jobs was down significantly from a
jump of 242,000 in June.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's probably going to be viewed as the most important
evidence that the Federal Reserve Board won't increase interest
rates at the end of August,'' said James Meyer, director of
research at Janney Montgomery Scott in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Investor optimism was limited to a narrow list of sectors,
namely banking and financial services stocks. J.P. Morgan led the
way, rising $6.438 to $141.438, and Merrill Lynch shares rose
$4.937 to $135.75.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of widely held technology stocks also saw gains,
helping to lift the Nasdaq stock market. Fiber-optics company Ciena
was up $5.625 to $147.563, software maker Oracle was up $3.687 at
$81.125, and Internet giant Yahoo! was up $1.437 at $132.625.
</P>
<P>
   But these gains were offset by losses to such bellwethers as
Intel, down $3.25 at $61.813, and Hewlett Packard, down $1.812 to
$110.313.
</P>
<P>
   Employment figures are watched closely because they are a key
barometer for inflationary pressures. Employers must pay higher
wages when demand for workers is high. Higher wages leads to higher
consumer prices and the onset of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board has raised interest rates six times
since last summer in an effort to stave off inflation, and
investors hope the latest figures are a sign that strategy is
working.
</P>
<P>
   If Fed members feel the same, they are more likely to leave
interest rates alone at their next meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4 to 3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 773.31 million
shares, down from Thursday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 3.65 at 503.10.
</P>
