<DOCNO> APW20000804.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Prepares for Flu Shot Shortage  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Worried about a possible shortage of this
winter's flu vaccine, federal health officials are studying whether
it would be safe to stretch supplies by giving some healthy
Americans half a dose, reserving full-strength vaccine for the
elderly and ill who need it most.
</P>
<P>
   Experts won't know until October if such a plan would work.
That's when they expect results of a clinical trial to measure
whether half a vaccine dose revs up certain people's immune systems
enough to protect them. Six hospitals will start recruiting 840
volunteers for the study next week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government is warning doctors and clinics that
flu shots will be shipped late this year -- meaning the healthy will
have to delay their shots a little while the elderly and others at
high risk of dying from the flu get vaccinated first.
</P>
<P>
   The government probably won't know until September if there also
will be a significant shortage of vaccine doses.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very clear there will be a delay in availability of
influenza vaccine,'' Dr. Nancy Cox of the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention said Friday. But, ''we don't know for sure
how much vaccine will be available.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem: Manufacturers had trouble growing one of the
influenza strains used in this year's vaccine. Because different
flu strains circle the globe each year, a new flu vaccine must be
brewed annually. In addition, the Food and Drug Administration
earlier this year ordered two of the nation's four vaccine makers
to correct manufacturing problems in their factories, delaying
production.
</P>
<P>
   The flu kills about 20,000 people every year. Most at risk are
people over age 64, and people of any age who have chronic heart or
lung diseases, including asthma, or who have diabetes, kidney
disease or a weakened immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect there would be enough vaccine to go around for those
who are at highest risk,'' Cox stressed.
</P>
<P>
   But because lots of healthy adults want flu shots too, the CDC
is urging health groups to ensure that high-risk patients get the
first available vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   If a doctor happens to get an early shipment of flu shots in
September or October, go ahead and vaccinate high-risk patients as
soon as possible, Cox advised.
</P>
<P>
   But companies, civic groups and others should postpone until
November -- a month late -- the annual mass-vaccination campaigns and
''flu-shot fairs'' that attract healthy, younger adults, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the half-dose vaccine theory, the National Institutes of
Health-funded study will begin recruiting healthy volunteers, ages
18 to 49, next week. Scientists will measure whether people given
half a dose of flu vaccine produce as many flu-fighting immune
cells as those who get a full vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Only healthy adults can test the half-dose theory -- and even if
a half-dose works for them, people at high risk of dying from flu
still would get the full dose, experts stressed.
</P>
<P>
   The study will be conducted at the University of Rochester, St.
Louis University, Baylor College of Medicine, University of
Maryland, Cincinnati Children's Hospital and the University of
California, Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Information on how to volunteer for the study will be posted
Tuesday on the following Internet site: http://clinicaltrials.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-04-00 1619 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
