<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Makes Recess Appointments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton on Friday made another round
of appointments with Congress not in session, including one that
drew opposition in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appointed John D. Holum as undersecretary of state for
arms control and international security. Holum's nomination had
been pending since March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The president also appointed George T. Frampton Jr. as chairman
of the Council on Environmental Quality, and Robert S. LaRussa as
an undersecretary for international trade at the Commerce
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Holum, a lawyer who previously served as legislative director
for former Sen. George McGovern, was among five Clinton nominees
considered unacceptable by a core group of GOP senators.
</P>
<P>
   The president gave recess appointments on Thursday to two of the
five: Bill Lann Lee, assistant attorney general for civil rights,
and Sally Katzen, deputy director for the Office of Management and
Budget.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution, the president can temporarily bypass the
Senate confirmation process by giving an individual an appointment
during a congressional recess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
