<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 61; Nasdaq Gains 27  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fluctuated for a second straight day
Friday, eventually closing higher on employment data that may point
to easing in the extremely tight job market.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose in early trading but fell
just as abruptly in response to the July employment figures. A
buying spree late in the session allowed blue chips stocks to close
up 61.17 at 10,767.75. For the week, the Dow rose 256.58.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index closed up 27.48 at 3,787.36, slipping
from a gain of more than 70 points earlier in the session. The
technology heavy index also swung wildly on Thursday; it ended the
week up 124.36.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.37 at 1,462.93, and
had a 43.04-point gain for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed Friday's volatility to indecisive investors
who don't know what to make of conflicting economic signals.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate was unchanged at 4 percent in
July, close to a three-decade low, despite the loss of 108,000
payroll jobs during the month, the biggest setback in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   But all the losses resulted from 290,000 temporary government
workers laid off in July because their work on the census was
finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department report showed private payrolls actually
rose by 138,000 during the month. However, analysts noted that last
month's gain in private sector jobs was down significantly from a
jump of 242,000 in June.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's probably going to be viewed as the most important
evidence that the Federal Reserve Board won't increase interest
rates at the end of August,'' said James Meyer, director of
research at Janney Montgomery Scott in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Broad-based investor optimism was limited to a narrow group of
sectors, however, namely banking and financial services stocks.
J.P. Morgan led the way, rising $8.25 to $143.25, and Merrill Lynch
shares rose $4.937 to $135.75.
</P>
<P>
   Banks will benefit if interest rates remain stable because
higher rates tend to curb lending and the lucrative business of
underwriting stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of widely held technology stocks also saw gains,
helping to lift the Nasdaq stock market. Fiber optics company Ciena
was up $6.75 to $148.688, software maker Oracle was up $4.125 at
$81.563, and Internet giant Yahoo! was up $2.75 at $133.938.
</P>
<P>
   But those gains were offset by losses to such bellwethers as
Intel, down $2.50 at $62.563, and drug maker Merck, down $1.187 at
$73.813.
</P>
<P>
   Employment figures are watched closely because they are a key
barometer for inflationary pressures. Employers must pay higher
wages when demand for workers is high. Higher wages lead to higher
consumer prices and the onset of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised interest rates six times since last summer in
an effort to stave off inflation, and investors hope the latest job
figures are a sign that strategy is working.
</P>
<P>
   If Fed members feel the same, they are more likely to leave
interest rates alone at their next meeting Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5 to 3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 1.12 billion shares,
down from Thursday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 4.18 at 503.63.
</P>
<P>
   In overseas trading, Japan's Nikkei fell 0.93 percent. In
London, the FT-SE 100 index rose 0.73 percent, while Paris' CAC
index gained 1.67 percent and Germany's DAX fell 0.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-04-00 1818 </TRAILER>
