<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio makes Clinton an offer: a moratorium on soft money  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON, N.Y. (AP) - Rick Lazio made Hillary Rodham Clinton
an offer she's already made: If she pledges not to use soft money
in her campaign, he'll do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by Arizona Sen. John McCain, known for pushing
campaign finance reform, the Republican candidate for New York's
Senate seat spoke during a visit Friday to a Long Island housing
project, saying he agreed with his fellow Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said that if soft money isn't taken out of all Senate
campaigns, the result will be ''an avalanche of negative ads which
the people of New York and the people of Arizona and the people of
this country don't want.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a former presidential candidate, said an
''out-of-control'' election system discourages Americans from
voting.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio claimed at least four soft-money accounts are financing
the Clinton campaign, and suggested there could be more.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign said there were only two accounts, and it
responded to Lazio's offer by pointing out that advisers to the
first lady had said in May that she would consider renouncing soft
money if her opponent did the same. But noting that Democrats had
already spent soft money on her behalf, the Lazio camp at the time
said the offer was nothing more than a political gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   On May 22, federal records showed that $542,000 in unregulated
campaign donations had been collected in two months for a special
Democratic account to help Clinton's Senate bid, bringing to more
than $1.2 million the amount of ''soft money'' taken in at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign manager Bill de Blasio charged that Lazio has
his own soft-money committee called Friends of Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming week, the Republican congressman from Long Island
will embark on an out-of-state fund-raising campaign, while Clinton
went to Martha's Vineyard for a weekend of fund-raising of her own,
with President Clinton at her side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-04-00 2014 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000804.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelton: All Army Divisions Ready  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREA CAVANAUGH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, said Friday that all of the Army's 10 divisions
are ready to meet their wartime requirements despite peacekeeping
commitments in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton was responding to a question at a public forum about a
comment made by Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush, who
said in his acceptance speech at the GOP convention that two Army
divisions were not combat ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''If called on by the commander-in-chief today, two entire
divisions of the Army would have to report, 'Not ready for duty,
sir,''' Bush said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused the Clinton administration of allowing U.S.
military might to erode.
</P>
<P>
   In October the commanders of the 1st Infantry Division and the
10th Mountain Division downgraded the readiness of their units
because portions of each division were deployed on peacekeeping
missions in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Those divisions have since reported that they are fully combat
ready, Shelton told an audience during questioning after a speech
to the Los Angeles World Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, who did not mention the issue in his speech, said he
was reluctant to comment on Bush's remarks, but added, ''National
security is so important it should be above politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials contacted Friday said the most current
readniess reports show all 10 of the Army's active divisions are
ready -- and have been for the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   In a report made public late last year, commanders of the two
divisions downgraded their units' readiness to C-4, the lowest of
four readiness ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The rating means that in a worst-case scenario of one major war
breaking out almost immediately after another in separate parts of
the world, these divisions could not get their troops to the fight
in the time prescribed by the Defense Department's war plan.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, elements of the 1st Infantry were in Kosovo and a
portion of the 10th Mountain Division was in Bosnia. Commanders
were concerned that the peacekeeping troops could not quickly
extract themselves and their equipment, return to their home bases,
retrain and then ship off to a major war in the allotted time.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton acknowledged that cuts in Pentagon budgets and personnel
during the past decade have taxed the military. Defense spending
and resources have been cut by 40 percent while commitments around
the world have increased 300 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are doing much more than we were doing 10 years ago, and we
are doing it with much less,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
