<HEADLINE> One of OTHER Democratic U.S. Senate candidates drops out of race  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - One of the five candidates challenging Hillary
Rodham Clinton in the upcoming Democratic primary for a U.S. Senate
candidate has dropped out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Ruano Melendez, a little-known civil engineer from New
York, announced his withdrawal Friday and instead endorsed the
first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she's the best candidate for this election and I don't
want to polarize my party,'' Melendez said.
</P>
<P>
   Melendez said that he intends to run for state senate against
Serphin Maltese in the general election instead.
</P>
<P>
   Melendez's departure from the race leaves Irving Gelb, Peter
Ruane, Dr. Mark McMahon, and Jimmy McMillan contesting with Clinton
in the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic primary is scheduled for Sept. 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
