<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police arrest suspect wanted in six Brooklyn killings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Police on Friday arrested a homeless man they
believe has killed six women in Brooklyn over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, identified as Vincent Johnson, who also goes by the
first name of Vinceny, was arrested Friday evening walking toward
Brooklyn on the Williamsburg Bridge, Detective John Giammarino
said. The 31-year-old man had not been charged as of late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday police announced that a connection had been made
in the cases and were looking for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ''A connection was made through forensic evidence, witness
accounts and the modus operandi of the victims that were killed,''
Deputy Chief Joseph Cuneen said.
</P>
<P>
   In all of the cases, the victims were strangled with whatever
their killer could find: two were strangled with their own
shoelaces, two with electrical cord, one with the drawstring from a
pair of sweatpants, and one with a piece of cloth.
</P>
<P>
   All the women had been arrested before for prostitution or
drug-related offenses, and all were found nude or partly clothed.
Their bodies were found in either Williamsburg or
Bedford-Stuyvesant.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Caraballo, 26, was the first victim - her body was found
on Aug. 26, 1999. Joanne Feliciano, 35, was found on Sept. 16,
1999. Rhonda Tucker, 21, was found on Sept. 25, 1999. In these
cases, DNA evidence suggested that the same man had had sex with
all these women, police have said. Cuneen would not discuss such
evidence on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth victim, Katrina Niles, 34, was found on Oct. 4, 1999.
A Jane Doe, believed to be 43, was found dead on Feb. 21, 2000. And
the last victim, Patricia Sullivan, 49, was found on June 22, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been arrested seven times in the city for various
offenses, including drug possession, criminal trespassing and theft
of services, Cuneen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
