<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Hits Russian Island  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A powerful earthquake struck the Russian island of
Sakhalin off the eastern coast of Siberia on Saturday, Russian and
U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of injuries, the Emergency
Situations Ministry in Moscow said.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake, which had a preliminary magnitude of 7.0, hit at
8:13 a.m. Saturday (5:13 p.m. EDT Friday), about 920 miles north of
Tokyo, according to the U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   Because the quake occurred on land, detection centers have not
issued a tsunami warning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a temblor registering 7.5 occurred about 240 miles
north of the latest earthquake. It killed almost 2,000 people and
caused severe damage. USGS spokeswoman Trudi Harlow said the latest
quake was much less forceful in terms of energy released.
</P>
</TEXT>
